      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, apologies! I get carried away; I've been trying to train a particularly stubborn goblin lately. The \"heavy goblin push\" refers to the mechanical tension, which is the direct, physical strain. When you apply high mechanical tension, it initiates mechanotransduction—a process where the physical force is translated into biochemical signals within the muscle cell. This mechanical signaling directly upregulates pathways like mTORC1, which is the master switch for muscle protein synthesis. Metabolic stress, meanwhile, acts more indirectly; the accumulation of metabolites triggers cellular stress responses that also contribute to the anabolic environment, often by influencing calcium handling and gene expression, but the direct mechanical loading is the more potent initiator of immediate protein synthesis signaling.\n\nIt's like this: High tension is the big, authoritative command from the chief goblin, forcing the workers (protein synthesis) to build bigger structures. Metabolic stress is the chaotic, buzzing energy of the lower-level goblins, creating a general state of necessary disruption that keeps the whole construction crew busy. Both contribute, but the tension provides the primary blueprint for growth.\n\nSo, to keep it purely scientific, the mechanical strain physically deforms the sarcomeres, which activates signaling cascades (like those involving integrins and",
      "source": "target",
